<div class="card">
  <div class="card-header">What is Nutrition?</div>
  <div class="p-3" role="article">
    <p><strong>Nutrition</strong> is the study of food and how it affects the health and growth of the body. <strong>Nutrients</strong> are substances found in foods that our bodies use to grow, reproduce and survive.</p>
    <p>There are <strong>6 major nutrients</strong> we get from food:</p>

    <ol class="nutrient-list">
      <li class="nutrient-item">
        <h4>Proteins</h4>
        <p>Proteins are important for growth and development. They also help your body repair tissue, carry oxygen, digest foods, and regulate hormones.</p>
        <p><strong>Sources:</strong> meat, legumes (beans, peas, lentils), nuts, seafood, and eggs.</p>
      </li>

      <li class="nutrient-item">
        <h4>Carbohydrates</h4>
        <p>Carbohydrates (a.k.a. carbs) are used for energy. Your body breaks carbs down into <em>glucose</em> which your cells use for energy.</p>
        <p><strong>Sources:</strong> pasta, bread, rice, potatoes, cereals, fruit, milk, sugar.</p>
      </li>

      <li class="nutrient-item">
        <h4>Lipids (a.k.a. fats)</h4>
        <p>Fats store energy, protect organs, support cell growth, and help your body absorb nutrients. There are two types: saturated (less healthy) and unsaturated (healthier).</p>
        <p><strong>Sources of unsaturated fats:</strong> oil, nuts, seeds, avocados, salmon.</p>
      </li>

      <li class="nutrient-item">
        <h4>Vitamins</h4>
        <p>Vitamins support many bodily functions. Examples:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>B vitamins:</strong> help release energy from carbs and fats, break down proteins, and transport oxygen.</li>
          <li><strong>Vitamin A:</strong> important for vision, growth, cell division, reproduction, and immunity.</li>
          <li><strong>Vitamin C:</strong> needed for forming blood vessels, cartilage, muscle, collagen, healing and iron absorption.</li>
          <li><strong>Vitamin D:</strong> needed for building and maintaining healthy bones.</li>
          <li><strong>Vitamin K:</strong> helps make proteins for blood clotting and bone building.</li>
        </ul>
      </li>

      <li class="nutrient-item">
        <h4>Minerals</h4>
        <p>Important minerals include:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Potassium:</strong> helps kidneys, heart, muscles and nerves work properly.</li>
          <li><strong>Sodium:</strong> helps nerves and muscles function and regulates fluid levels.</li>
          <li><strong>Calcium:</strong> forms bones and teeth.</li>
          <li><strong>Phosphorus:</strong> contributes to healthy bones and DNA/RNA formation.</li>
          <li><strong>Magnesium:</strong> supports muscle/nerve function and energy production.</li>
          <li><strong>Zinc:</strong> supports immune system and metabolism.</li>
          <li><strong>Iron:</strong> needed to form red blood cells.</li>
        </ul>
      </li>

      <li class="nutrient-item">
        <h4>Water</h4>
        <p>Water is essential — human bodies are ~60% water. It helps regulate temperature, lubricate joints, protect the spinal cord, and remove wastes.</p>
      </li>
    </ol>

    <p>As you can see, each of these nutrients plays an important role in your health. Research shows people who eat healthier tend to live longer and have lower risk of serious diseases such as heart disease, type 2 diabetes, and obesity.</p>

    <div class="source">
      <p><strong>So where can I learn how to eat a nutritious diet?</strong></p>
      <p>A great place to start is <a href="https://www.myplate.gov" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">MyPlate.gov</a> — it helps you understand how much of each food group to eat each day. You can also stop by the Quincy Student Health and Wellness Center for help.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>